    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks for that. that makes sense. but there's another part in the same section that talks about \"third-party claims.\" it says i'd have to cover them too if someone else sues the client because of my work. that sounds kind of scary. are there any specific risks or \"hidden\" things i should be looking out for in this kind of clause?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The \"third-party claims\" part can be a bit unsettling, but it's actually a common provision in contracts like this. It's essentially saying that if someone else sues the Client because of your work, and that person can prove that you were negligent or reckless, then you'll have to cover their costs and damages, in addition to the Client's. It's not necessarily \"hidden,\" but it's worth being aware of the potential risks, especially if you're working on a high-risk project or with sensitive information.\n\nOne thing to keep in mind is that this clause can also apply if someone sues the Client for something that's not directly related to your work, but you're still somehow connected to the project (e.g., if you're a subcontractor or partner with the Client). It's a bit like having a \"goblin in the shadows\" clause, where you're not directly responsible for the Client's mistakes, but you're still on the hook if someone else sues because of your indirect involvement.",
      "source": "target",
